In the context of preventing DOM-based XSS attacks, it is crucial to ensure that any user input that gets inserted into the document object model (DOM) is properly sanitized and escaped. Here's a simple JavaScript example demonstrating how one might safely handle user inputs to mitigate XSS risks:

### Example Secure Implementation:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<title>Safe User Input Handling</title>
<script>
function displayUserMessage() {
    // Retrieve user message from URL parameter
    const userInput = new URLSearchParams(window.location.search).get('message');

    // Sanitize the input to escape HTML entities
    const safeInput = sanitizeHTML(userInput);

    // Insert sanitized content into the DOM
    document.getElementById("output").innerHTML = safeInput;
}

// Function to sanitize HTML input
function sanitizeHTML(htmlString) {
    var tempDiv = document.createElement('div');
    tempDiv.textContent = htmlString; // Sets innerText instead of innerHTML
    return tempDiv.innerHTML;
}
</script>
</head>
<body onload="displayUserMessage()">
<div id="output"></div>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, `sanitizeHTML` function uses `textContent` to set text within a temporary div which automatically escapes any potentially dangerous characters like `<`, `>`, `'`, `"`, etc., ensuring that no script tags or other harmful elements are executed when rendered back into the page via `innerHTML`.

This approach ensures that even if an attacker tries to inject malicious scripts, they will be treated as plain text due to escaping mechanisms rather than executable code.

